ue="pedv---00001004-20180327-161428"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:gvtre"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:gvbod"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001004-20180327-161428"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI><CodeI org="hierarchy" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001004-20180327-161428"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="2"/></CodeI></Code><Code value="gvbod"><CodeD index="no" lang="en">Government Bodies</CodeD><CodeI org="rbc" action="add"><CodeA name="rule" value="860177"/><CodeA name="db" value="prbc---00018595-20180328-074858"/></CodeI><CodeI org="expansion" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001004-20180327-161428"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:gvtre"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001004-20180327-161428"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI><CodeI org="hierarchy" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001004-20180327-161428"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="3"/></CodeI></Code><Code value="gcns"><CodeD index="no" lang="en">National/Public Security</CodeD><CodeI org="expansion" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001004-20180327-161428"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:gsec"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001004-20180327-161428"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI><CodeI org="hierarchy" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001004-20180327-161428"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="1"/></CodeI></Code><Code value="gvexe"><CodeD index="no" lang="en">Executive Branch</CodeD><CodeI org="expansion" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001004-20180327-161428"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:gvtre"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001004-20180327-161428"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI><CodeI org="hierarchy" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001004-20180327-161428"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="4"/></CodeI></Code></CSet></CodeSets><DescTPC fid="de"><DescField fid="ipc">G/IGV G/TRE N/GEN N/PLT R/ASI R/CH R/FEO R/NME R/US </DescField><DescField fid="ipd">WSJ WSJ.com WSJ.com Site Search WSJAsia WSJEurope WSJ Japanese Online WSJ-PRO-WSJ.com WSJSunday PTC NATIONAL SECURITY TRADE BARRIERS TRADE DEFICITS TRADE PROTECTIONISM TRADE WAR TRUMP CHINA TRUMP TRADE U.S. TECH SB127189489785985032805045841293634350880561 Malpass, David SYND CODES_REVIEWED Politics and Policy </DescField><DescField fid="ipcns">OPOL </DescField></DescTPC></MetadataPT><ArchiveDoc xml:space="preserve"><Article markup="pp0" lang="en" index="field"><HandL fid="hlp"><Title fid="hl"><SectionName fid="se" index="field">Politics</SectionName><ColumnName fid="clm" index="field"></ColumnName><Headline fid="hd"><Para lang="en">Treasury to Use National Security Laws to Shield U.S. Tech From China; Move part of Trump administration's efforts to foil what it sees as Beijing's efforts to gain an advantage</Para></Headline></Title><LeadPara fid="lp"><Para>WASHINGTONâ€”The U.S. Treasury Department is planning to use laws designed to address national emergencies to block Chinese firms from acquiring advanced U.S. technology, part of a Trump administration initiative to thwart what it sees as Beijing's efforts to give itself an economic and military edge, according to administration officials.</Para><Para>The Trump administration is looking to use a number of legal measures in its arsenal, including the International Emergency Economic Powers Act of 1977, or IEEPA, which gives the president broad authority in the case of an "unusual and extraordinary threat," according to a senior official familiar with administration plans. The law was widely employed after the Sept. 11, 2001 terrorist attacks to impose sanctions on other countries, and observers say courts haven't questioned the usage of the law.</Para></LeadPara></HandL><TailParas fid="td"><Para>Gary Hufbauer a legal trade expert at the Peterson Institute for International Economics, said in a report that the strategy could give Mr. Trump "a free hand" to address the administration's concern about Chinese trade and investment practices.</Para><Para>The plan to expand restrictions on Chinese investment comes on top of both existing export control regulations and a congressional effort to strengthen national-security approvals by the Committee on Foreign Investment in the U.S., a multiagency watchdog that reviews foreign acquisitions in the U.S. for national security risks.</Para><Para>President Trump signaled the new restrictions last week, when he announced the U.S. would levy tariffs on up to $60 billion in Chinese imports in response to Beijing's efforts to obtain U.S. technology through intimidation, state-finance acquisition and theft. But, at the time, he provided few details.</Para><Para>The Treasury has been working on the investment project for several months, an administration official said. The U.S. would argue that Beijing's investment rules are fundamentally unfair to U.S. companies, and that China has slid backward in its reform efforts. It's licensing requirements, subsidized financing, involvement of state-owned firms and pressure on U.S. firms to transfer technology are all increasingly harming U.S. technology firms, the official said.</Para><Para>"The hope was that China would develop into a fair, reciprocal and market-oriented partner for trade and investment," said Treasury Undersecretary David Malpass at the Foreign Policy Association earlier this month, foreshadowing the Treasury effort. "Instead, China's market liberalization has stalled and even reversed, with the role of the state increasing."</Para><Para>To press China to change course, the U.S. would block China's acquisition of what the official at one point called "core aspects of key technologies" and another point referred to as "critical technology." Mr. Trump gave Treasury 60 days to devise the plans.</Para><Para>Although the rationale for the investment restrictions is a lack of reciprocity, the administration official said that the U.S. wouldn't respond to China on a tit-for-tat basis. China requires many U.S. companies to form joint ventures to do business in China, for instance, but the U.S. isn't planning similar restrictions on Beijing firms operating in the U.S. The U.S. would respond, the official said, with a blanket restriction on certain kinds of technology acquisition, whether through outright acquisitions, joint ventures, licensing or other means.</Para><Para>Despite the threats of tariffs from the U.S. and retaliation from China, the two sides have quietly begun negotiations aimed at heading off a trade war. If those talks bear fruit, it is possible that none of the restrictions being discussed will be put into effectâ€”or only some of them, U.S. officials say.</Para><Para>Mr. Hufbauer said, in an interview, he worried that the U.S. would define critical technology too broadly and harm investment into the U.S. "They would be going in a way that will greatly restrict two-way investment between the U.S. and China," he said. "It will open up Chinese investment to Japanese and European firms (rather than U.S. ones). It is overkill."</Para><Para>Myron Brilliant, executive vice president of the U.S. Chamber of Commerce, which has been warning about Chinese trading practices and technology plans, said it was important to address Beijing policies "that prop up Chinese companies and harm U.S. firms' ability to operate in China." But he warned about going too far. "It's important that we recognize the need for constructive engagement with China as the economic relationship between the two countries is too big to fail," he said.</Para><Para>The Treasury will have to address many thorny questions in developing rules. Just defining what percentage of equity would classify a firm as "state-owned" is difficult, as is the definition of which technologies should be off limits. In some cases, U.S. firms could rely on Chinese ones for innovation, especially in manufacturing.</Para><Para>The U.S. has focused on technologies listed in a Chinese government report called, "Made in China 2025," released in 2015, which is a blueprint for making China a world leader in a number of technology areas, including robotics, semiconductors and electric vehicles. But that was simply a blueprint in a country that produces five-year plans by the dozens.</Para><Para>The U.S. would also be looking at the kinds of actions Beijing has been taking to put the plan into effect, the official said.</Para><Para>One avenue the Treasury isn't pursuing, the official said, is remaking U.S. tariffs so that they would be based on the concept of reciprocity. President Trump regularly complains others countries take advantage of the U.S. in international trade because U.S. tariffs are sometimes lower than those of its trading partners. He has focused on China's 25% tariff on imported cars, compared with the U.S.'s 2.5% levy.</Para><Para>"The word is reciprocal." Mr. Trump said in the White House ceremony announcing the tariff and investment restrictions. "Some people call it a mirror tariff or a mirror tax. If they charge us, we charge them the same thing."</Para><Para>But an administration official said the Treasury isn't pursuing an overall change in tariffs along these lines. A second administration official said no plan of that sort had been sent to the White House for review.</Para><Para>Write to Bob Davis at <ELink type="webpage" ref="mailto:bob.davis@wsj.com">bob.davis@wsj.com</ELink></Para></TailParas><Byline fid="by" index="field">By Bob Davis </Byline><Credit fid="cr" index="field"></Credit><Contact fid="ct" index="field"></Contact><Notes fid="rf" index="field"></Notes><Art fid="art" index="field"></Art><Copyright fid="cy" index="field">Copyright 2018 Dow Jones &amp; Company, Inc. All Rights Reserved. </Copyright></Article></ArchiveDoc><AdocTOC adoctype="article"><Item size="0" r